WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.640
So, without further ado, I'd like to introduce our first speaker, Will Chase, speaking on

00:00:10.640 --> 00:00:15.040
The Glamour of Graphics.

00:00:15.040 --> 00:00:28.520
Alright, so, thank you for coming today, everyone, and welcome to my talk on The Glamour of Graphics,

00:00:28.520 --> 00:00:32.439
which is a talk on the design of charts.

00:00:32.439 --> 00:00:35.119
So if you recognize me, it's probably from Twitter.

00:00:35.119 --> 00:00:42.799
I tweet excessively, and you may also recognize my website, williamrchase.com, where I post

00:00:42.799 --> 00:00:49.599
lots of blogs about art and generative art, how to make it an R, R tutorials, all sorts

00:00:49.599 --> 00:00:51.840
of stuff like that.

00:00:51.840 --> 00:00:54.720
So professionally, I come from academia.

00:00:54.720 --> 00:00:59.480
I worked at Penn State and then UPenn for many years, and now recently I've joined Fidelity

00:00:59.480 --> 00:01:06.440
Investments as a senior visualization analyst, where I'm focusing on visual design and storytelling

00:01:06.440 --> 00:01:07.440
within our organization.

00:01:07.440 --> 00:01:12.160
I also do freelance data visualization, so if you're interested in talking about that,

00:01:12.160 --> 00:01:14.279
please get in touch.

00:01:14.279 --> 00:01:18.080
Now, The Glamour of Graphics that I'm going to be talking about today was actually inspired

00:01:18.080 --> 00:01:19.919
by Kelly Bodwin.

00:01:19.919 --> 00:01:24.320
As I say, I tweet excessively, so this is where I got the inspiration, and that led

00:01:24.320 --> 00:01:31.040
me to spend one of my Saturdays making this Glamour Magazine spoof, which I think was

00:01:31.040 --> 00:01:36.599
probably my most viral tweet ever, and I may be the first person to get invited to talk

00:01:36.599 --> 00:01:41.559
at RStudioConf based on a Twitter meme that I made, so I'm pretty proud of that.

00:01:41.559 --> 00:01:43.440
But I think that there's actually some substance here.

00:01:43.440 --> 00:01:46.720
So this said take your charts from drab to fab, and that's sort of what we're going to

00:01:46.720 --> 00:01:48.419
try to do today.

00:01:48.419 --> 00:01:49.720
So this is the drab.

00:01:49.720 --> 00:01:51.199
This is the starting point, right?

00:01:51.720 --> 00:01:54.400
But it's true.

00:01:54.400 --> 00:01:58.080
And what we're going to try to do is get something more like this.

00:01:58.080 --> 00:02:00.000
So a little bit about what this talk is not.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:05.720
It's not a talk about chart shaming, so you'll see a lot of design mistakes that I'm going

00:02:05.720 --> 00:02:09.600
to talk about today, but if you go to my blog and look at my portfolio, you will see all

00:02:09.600 --> 00:02:12.839
of those mistakes featured heavily there.

00:02:12.839 --> 00:02:18.440
It's also not a talk about tools or about what charts to use in terms of data visualization.

00:02:18.440 --> 00:02:20.960
It's really focused on the aesthetics.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:24.520
So the reason you should care about aesthetics and charts is pretty obvious to me, but it

00:02:24.520 --> 00:02:28.360
will help you engage a much wider audience with your work.

00:02:28.360 --> 00:02:32.199
It'll actually help your work to be perceived as more usable and more intuitive.

00:02:32.199 --> 00:02:36.080
So it's actually been shown that charts that are more aesthetically pleasing are perceived

00:02:36.080 --> 00:02:38.559
by users to be more intuitive.

00:02:38.559 --> 00:02:41.199
And finally, it'll just let you show respect for your audience.

00:02:41.199 --> 00:02:43.279
People spend their time looking at your charts.

00:02:43.279 --> 00:02:46.440
You should spend time making them look nice.

00:02:46.440 --> 00:02:49.800
So when I started researching this, I thought it was sort of just a coincidence.

00:02:49.800 --> 00:02:53.119
So grammar of graphics, glamour of graphics, ha ha.

00:02:53.119 --> 00:02:57.639
But it turns out that the word glamour is actually derived from the word grammar.

00:02:57.639 --> 00:03:02.279
So back in the Middle Ages, the word grammar meant all learning, and that included things

00:03:02.279 --> 00:03:05.800
like magic and occult.

00:03:05.800 --> 00:03:10.800
And through the ages, that word sort of morphed into glamour, and as it did, it lost the association

00:03:10.800 --> 00:03:16.199
with knowledge, and it became to mean just a magical spell, actually.

00:03:16.199 --> 00:03:20.039
And then eventually in the 18th century, the idea of magic sort of washed away a little

00:03:20.039 --> 00:03:25.199
bit and we got the meaning that we know today, which is this sort of exciting, illusory,

00:03:25.199 --> 00:03:27.839
romantic attractiveness.

00:03:27.839 --> 00:03:31.940
So the grammar of graphics is a tool that enables us to concisely describe the components

00:03:31.940 --> 00:03:33.800
of a graphic.

00:03:33.800 --> 00:03:37.800
And what I'm going to do today is try to bring this sort of illusory, romantic quality of

00:03:37.800 --> 00:03:40.660
glamour a little bit closer to a grammar.

00:03:40.660 --> 00:03:46.039
So I'm going to describe a tool that enables us to concisely describe the design of a graphic.

00:03:46.039 --> 00:03:51.240
So in the grammar of graphics, we have these three components of data, aesthetics, and

00:03:51.240 --> 00:03:53.720
geometries that are really the core of any chart.

00:03:53.720 --> 00:03:58.720
And I know there's more layers, but this is really the core of how to describe a chart.

00:03:58.720 --> 00:04:02.520
What I'm going to describe in the glamour of graphics is similar, but I'm going to describe

00:04:02.520 --> 00:04:06.600
three layers that you need to describe the design of a graphic, and that's the layout,

00:04:06.600 --> 00:04:09.639
the typography, and the color.

00:04:09.639 --> 00:04:15.240
So beginning with layout, I'm going to talk about three main concepts today, and that

00:04:15.240 --> 00:04:20.559
is alignment, white space, and grids, lines, and borders.

00:04:20.559 --> 00:04:24.799
So beginning with alignment, I want to talk about titles first.

00:04:24.799 --> 00:04:29.600
Titles should be top-left aligned, usually.

00:04:29.600 --> 00:04:34.040
And when I say top-left aligned, I don't mean the case that you see on the left where you

00:04:34.040 --> 00:04:35.679
have left-aligned with your data.

00:04:35.679 --> 00:04:40.119
I mean left-aligned all the way to the edge of your chart to create a nice, clean line

00:04:40.119 --> 00:04:41.440
with the edge of your chart.

00:04:41.760 --> 00:04:45.079
Now, previously, this was actually kind of tricky to do with ggplot, but luckily in the

00:04:45.079 --> 00:04:50.359
development version, we have a new argument that makes this very, very simple to do.

00:04:50.359 --> 00:04:57.480
Next, I want you to please not make me do, like, this when I read your chart.

00:04:57.480 --> 00:05:01.640
So I see this a lot of times, especially in academic graphics, where you have these really

00:05:01.640 --> 00:05:04.600
long X-axis labels.

00:05:04.600 --> 00:05:05.640
Nobody wants to do that.

00:05:05.640 --> 00:05:10.480
So of course, it's always better if you can to flip our coordinates horizontally, or if

00:05:10.480 --> 00:05:14.119
you can't manage to flip it, you can just try to make the text horizontal by increasing

00:05:14.119 --> 00:05:16.480
your spacing and such.

00:05:16.480 --> 00:05:19.959
This is a little more controversial, maybe, but I also think it's actually best practice

00:05:19.959 --> 00:05:24.679
not to use vertical axis labels, because you have the same problem.

00:05:24.679 --> 00:05:25.679
So you can do the same thing.

00:05:25.679 --> 00:05:29.480
You can try to make the text just horizontal, or a lot of times, you can get rid of axis

00:05:29.480 --> 00:05:31.480
labels entirely.

00:05:31.480 --> 00:05:33.959
A lot of axis labels are completely unnecessary.

00:05:33.959 --> 00:05:39.600
Things like dates, in this case, SUV, minivan, it's obvious these are types of cars.

00:05:39.600 --> 00:05:46.079
And usually by just including a good title, you can do away with axis labels.

00:05:46.079 --> 00:05:50.200
So when you're thinking about alignment, you should always try to create clean lines and

00:05:50.200 --> 00:05:51.440
symmetry.

00:05:51.440 --> 00:05:55.440
And what I want to go over is a little bit, this graphic from 538 that I think really

00:05:55.440 --> 00:05:57.619
illustrates some of these points.

00:05:57.619 --> 00:06:01.299
So this doesn't have big blocks of text, but just to mention, if you do have big blocks

00:06:01.299 --> 00:06:06.200
of text, like an infographic or something, you want to left align those, most likely.

00:06:06.200 --> 00:06:09.600
Left alignment should sort of be your default.

00:06:09.600 --> 00:06:14.320
Right alignment can be used for labels a lot of times, so especially like horizontal bar

00:06:14.320 --> 00:06:19.119
labels, where the goal is to create a clean line with the edge of your data.

00:06:19.119 --> 00:06:24.359
And sometimes subtitles or labels can be center aligned if it helps to create symmetry within

00:06:24.359 --> 00:06:25.880
the graphic.

00:06:25.880 --> 00:06:29.839
So in this case, you can see, actually, the designer made a mistake on the 2014 one.

00:06:29.839 --> 00:06:33.220
It should be center aligned, but it's slightly off center.

00:06:33.220 --> 00:06:36.940
But if you look at the rest of the graphic, you can see how this left alignment, right

00:06:36.940 --> 00:06:42.959
alignment, and center alignment sort of creates this perfect symmetry within the graphic.

00:06:42.959 --> 00:06:46.179
So charts often come with these extraneous elements.

00:06:46.179 --> 00:06:50.339
They're not data, and a lot of times they can distract from the chart.

00:06:50.339 --> 00:06:53.700
So I want to talk a little bit about how to reduce those.

00:06:53.700 --> 00:06:55.820
A good example of this is borders.

00:06:55.820 --> 00:06:58.899
You almost never need a border in a chart.

00:06:58.899 --> 00:07:02.540
Oftentimes they just don't serve a purpose, and all they do is distract from your data,

00:07:02.540 --> 00:07:05.260
and add ink to the page.

00:07:05.260 --> 00:07:07.540
Another thing is gridlines.

00:07:07.540 --> 00:07:11.459
I understand that there's reasons to have gridlines sometimes, but I encourage you to

00:07:11.459 --> 00:07:13.940
always question the purpose of every gridline.

00:07:13.940 --> 00:07:16.380
Do you need horizontal gridlines in every case?

00:07:16.380 --> 00:07:18.700
Do you need minor gridlines?

00:07:18.700 --> 00:07:21.140
If not, please remove them.

00:07:21.140 --> 00:07:26.179
If you do need them, I encourage you to make them as light and as small as possible so

00:07:26.179 --> 00:07:31.619
that they sort of disappear into the background rather than distracting from your data.

00:07:31.619 --> 00:07:35.399
Another thing that distracts from your data a lot is legends, particularly when you have

00:07:35.399 --> 00:07:39.700
like a big blob of a legend off to the right-hand side of your chart.

00:07:39.700 --> 00:07:41.420
It's not a very good flow within your chart.

00:07:41.420 --> 00:07:44.779
So I recommend if you have legends, you put them right below the titles where it creates

00:07:44.779 --> 00:07:47.140
a nice flow with your chart.

00:07:47.140 --> 00:07:50.980
A better solution even is to directly label your data.

00:07:50.980 --> 00:07:58.160
Or my favorite solution is to use colored text to indicate your legend in the title.

00:07:58.160 --> 00:08:02.000
And this will now be possible with the new grid text package, which I think Klaus is

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:05.559
talking about this afternoon.

00:08:05.559 --> 00:08:09.200
So a few words about whitespace.

00:08:09.200 --> 00:08:12.920
This is particularly relevant when you're looking at things like dashboards and infographics

00:08:12.920 --> 00:08:15.500
where you're laying out a lot of charts together.

00:08:15.500 --> 00:08:19.440
And what I often see is people want to cram as much information as they can possibly get

00:08:19.440 --> 00:08:21.299
onto the page.

00:08:21.299 --> 00:08:26.760
But what that ends up resulting in is that you can't even understand any of it.

00:08:26.760 --> 00:08:29.040
Your eye has no idea where to go on the page.

00:08:29.040 --> 00:08:32.099
And so your charts really need room to breathe.

00:08:32.099 --> 00:08:34.119
So I always recommend it's like garlic.

00:08:34.119 --> 00:08:40.000
You take as much whitespace as you think you need and then triple it.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:43.940
So that's sort of the foundation of building a nice chart is the layout.

00:08:43.940 --> 00:08:47.679
And next up I'm going to talk about typography.

00:08:47.679 --> 00:08:51.159
So typography is a very sort of vast subject.

00:08:51.159 --> 00:08:52.880
It has a lot of details in it.

00:08:52.880 --> 00:08:54.200
And I can't cover them all today.

00:08:54.200 --> 00:08:59.159
But what I highly, highly recommend you do is go to practicaltypography.com.

00:08:59.159 --> 00:09:03.820
This is a completely free open source online book that will basically teach you everything

00:09:03.820 --> 00:09:07.559
you could need to know about typography in a very concise way.

00:09:07.559 --> 00:09:11.919
It will take about three hours to read cover to cover and it will vastly improve the design

00:09:11.919 --> 00:09:14.919
of everything that you write.

00:09:14.919 --> 00:09:21.840
But I do want to touch a little bit on fonts, hierarchy, and a couple of data specific concerns.

00:09:21.840 --> 00:09:24.799
The font that you choose really matters in a chart.

00:09:24.799 --> 00:09:28.080
It especially affects the tone of your graphic, right?

00:09:28.080 --> 00:09:32.200
You can send a completely different message based on the font you choose.

00:09:32.200 --> 00:09:36.039
And it can also really affect the legibility of your graphic, right?

00:09:36.039 --> 00:09:42.719
It's pretty easy to have misunderstandings if you choose the wrong font.

00:09:42.719 --> 00:09:46.280
So this is important.

00:09:46.280 --> 00:09:50.200
And the unfortunate thing is that most people will just go for the system font.

00:09:50.200 --> 00:09:51.760
The default font.

00:09:51.760 --> 00:09:57.000
And that's sad because most system fonts are pretty terrible, I'm sorry to tell you.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:01.679
Most of them were designed for the screens that we had in the 1990s, which were all pixelated

00:10:01.679 --> 00:10:02.679
and terrible.

00:10:02.679 --> 00:10:05.599
And on modern screens, they look pretty ugly.

00:10:05.599 --> 00:10:09.140
So if you're a professional organization, you might buy a professional font.

00:10:09.140 --> 00:10:12.559
But for most of you in the room, you'll probably be looking at free fonts.

00:10:12.559 --> 00:10:16.919
And the good news is that in 2020, we have a wealth of wonderfully designed beautiful

00:10:16.919 --> 00:10:21.799
free fonts available easily at fonts.google.com.

00:10:21.799 --> 00:10:24.679
These are some of my favorites for data visualization.

00:10:24.679 --> 00:10:26.200
I really like the Source family.

00:10:26.200 --> 00:10:32.520
It has a Sans Serif variety, Serif variety, monospaced variety, and they're all available

00:10:32.520 --> 00:10:35.760
in lots of weights and sizes.

00:10:35.760 --> 00:10:40.460
So next I want to touch a little bit on hierarchy, a typographic hierarchy.

00:10:40.460 --> 00:10:46.280
So a typographic hierarchy is just a way of encoding an order of importance in your type

00:10:46.280 --> 00:10:51.520
that helps to navigate your readers through your chart or through your document.

00:10:51.520 --> 00:10:53.219
And there's several ways to create hierarchy.

00:10:53.219 --> 00:10:55.479
So this is a case where we have none.

00:10:55.479 --> 00:10:58.880
The easiest way to create hierarchy is with size.

00:10:58.880 --> 00:11:04.179
You can also do it with font weight, with color, with spacing.

00:11:04.179 --> 00:11:07.440
You can do it with a contrasting typeface.

00:11:07.440 --> 00:11:10.640
Or ideally a combination of all of these things.

00:11:10.640 --> 00:11:14.320
And learning the rules of how to create a hierarchy, you know, what should you make

00:11:14.359 --> 00:11:18.640
your title versus your subtitle versus your body text is just a skill that takes a little

00:11:18.640 --> 00:11:19.940
bit of practice.

00:11:19.940 --> 00:11:23.799
But there are some more specific tips in the Practical Typography book that I mentioned

00:11:23.799 --> 00:11:25.760
earlier.

00:11:25.760 --> 00:11:27.719
And finally I want to talk about numbers a little bit.

00:11:27.719 --> 00:11:32.000
So we use numbers all the time in data visualization.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:34.039
Some fonts have what's called old style numbers.

00:11:34.039 --> 00:11:36.599
I recommend you not use these.

00:11:36.599 --> 00:11:41.719
Most of those fonts will also have lining numbers, which have all the same X height.

00:11:41.719 --> 00:11:46.000
And in a similar vein, you also want to choose a font that has tabular numbers.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:48.159
Tabular numbers all have the same width.

00:11:48.159 --> 00:11:51.760
So that when you make a table or something, everything will line up in a nice perfect

00:11:51.760 --> 00:11:54.940
column.

00:11:54.940 --> 00:12:00.159
So having covered the layout and the typography of a chart, I want to talk a little bit about

00:12:00.159 --> 00:12:01.159
the color.

00:12:01.159 --> 00:12:02.159
Everyone's favorite topic.

00:12:02.159 --> 00:12:05.340
So there's a lot of tools out there I know.

00:12:05.340 --> 00:12:08.719
People are probably familiar with things like Color Brewer and there's other R packages

00:12:08.719 --> 00:12:11.400
that will basically just choose a color for you.

00:12:11.400 --> 00:12:13.359
Choose a color palette for you.

00:12:13.359 --> 00:12:17.159
What I want to do today is try to give you a little bit of information that will hopefully

00:12:17.159 --> 00:12:21.400
help you to choose your own color palettes.

00:12:21.400 --> 00:12:23.140
The truth is, though, that color is really hard.

00:12:23.140 --> 00:12:25.919
So I don't want to lie to you and tell you it's going to be easy.

00:12:25.919 --> 00:12:27.960
It's something I still struggle with.

00:12:27.960 --> 00:12:31.599
And it's just such a complex subject that it takes a lot of practice.

00:12:31.599 --> 00:12:35.559
But I think there are a few things that I can tell you today about color theory and

00:12:35.559 --> 00:12:40.780
then a few sort of practical tips to help improve your usage of color.

00:12:40.859 --> 00:12:43.739
So one of the chief complaints I get from people is they say, I just don't know what

00:12:43.739 --> 00:12:45.059
colors look good together.

00:12:45.059 --> 00:12:47.419
How do I know what looks good together?

00:12:47.419 --> 00:12:49.700
This is a case where the color wheel can really help you.

00:12:49.700 --> 00:12:55.859
So the color wheel, like we all know from grade school, it looks like this.

00:12:55.859 --> 00:12:59.539
And there's several types of palettes you can choose from the color wheel that will

00:12:59.539 --> 00:13:02.679
usually have colors that go well together.

00:13:02.679 --> 00:13:06.299
So if you want to choose a high contrast palette, you can choose a complementary one.

00:13:06.299 --> 00:13:09.219
That means opposite sides of the color wheel.

00:13:09.219 --> 00:13:12.619
You can also choose analogous color palettes, which all come from the same side of the color

00:13:12.619 --> 00:13:13.940
wheel.

00:13:13.940 --> 00:13:17.440
And there's triadic, which are sort of laid out in a triangle like this.

00:13:17.440 --> 00:13:21.700
And there's several other color palettes as well.

00:13:21.700 --> 00:13:25.599
There's split complementary, quadratic, and lots of others.

00:13:25.599 --> 00:13:28.539
And you can read a little bit more about sort of the feeling that all these color palettes

00:13:28.539 --> 00:13:29.539
give you.

00:13:29.539 --> 00:13:34.619
But this is a nice way to sort of get started if you're looking to choose some hues.

00:13:34.619 --> 00:13:37.020
So once you choose those, you might want to adjust your colors a little bit.

00:13:37.140 --> 00:13:39.380
And I want to highlight the HSL color space.

00:13:39.380 --> 00:13:43.739
So this is a way of describing color in contrast to something like RGB.

00:13:43.739 --> 00:13:47.900
HSL stands for the hue, saturation, and lightness of a color.

00:13:47.900 --> 00:13:51.700
So the hue is the actual color itself, red, green, blue.

00:13:51.700 --> 00:13:55.500
The saturation is the amount of color you have there.

00:13:55.500 --> 00:13:58.859
And the lightness is how light or dark a color is.

00:13:58.859 --> 00:14:01.419
So this is an example where we have a red hue.

00:14:01.419 --> 00:14:05.020
And if we turn down the saturation, you can see that it will basically drain all the color

00:14:05.020 --> 00:14:06.020
out of there.

00:14:07.020 --> 00:14:12.380
If we turn up the saturation, it's going to become very rich and vibrant.

00:14:12.380 --> 00:14:15.539
And if we turn down the lightness, we can see we still have a richness here, but now

00:14:15.539 --> 00:14:17.859
it's much darker.

00:14:17.859 --> 00:14:20.659
And if we turn it up, it'll become more lighter, obviously.

00:14:20.659 --> 00:14:24.659
But you can see how this is a very easy way when you pick a color and you say, oh, but

00:14:24.659 --> 00:14:28.380
I wish it were a little bit lighter or a little bit more saturated or less saturated.

00:14:28.380 --> 00:14:32.539
This is a much more intuitive mental model, I think, of how to adjust your colors.

00:14:32.539 --> 00:14:37.460
And there's lots of online tools you can use where you can stick it in and it'll allow

00:14:37.460 --> 00:14:43.619
you to adjust the sliders a little bit for your saturation and lightness and such.

00:14:43.619 --> 00:14:45.539
So that was a little bit of the color theory.

00:14:45.539 --> 00:14:49.179
Now some of the practicalities of how I choose color.

00:14:49.179 --> 00:14:51.460
So I'm sort of a color pirate.

00:14:51.460 --> 00:14:56.679
I use my favorite tool in the world all the time, which is the eyedropper tool.

00:14:56.679 --> 00:15:00.260
So this is a tool, if you're not familiar, it's present in all kinds of design programs

00:15:00.780 --> 00:15:02.460
and you can get apps on your computer.

00:15:02.460 --> 00:15:05.859
On my Mac, I like to use one called Color Slurp.

00:15:05.859 --> 00:15:10.700
On Windows, I like Instant Eyedropper, where you can just click the tool, pick any pixel

00:15:10.700 --> 00:15:13.659
on your screen, and it'll return the color for you.

00:15:13.659 --> 00:15:17.140
So I use this all the time if I see a data visualization, for example, that I really

00:15:17.140 --> 00:15:21.340
like where I love the color palette, I'll just take my eyedropper, pick those colors.

00:15:21.340 --> 00:15:26.739
I do this with websites, with photographs, and then I use the HSL sliders to adjust the

00:15:26.739 --> 00:15:27.739
colors afterwards.

00:15:28.539 --> 00:15:33.539
A good example of this is this generative conference badge that I designed this summer.

00:15:33.539 --> 00:15:36.340
And I got the inspiration from my mom's day planner.

00:15:36.340 --> 00:15:39.460
So I went to visit my parents and saw this day planner and I really liked it, so I just

00:15:39.460 --> 00:15:40.940
took a picture of it.

00:15:40.940 --> 00:15:44.700
And when it came time to design the graphic, I took my eyedropper tool, picked all the

00:15:44.700 --> 00:15:49.700
colors I liked, adjusted them a little bit with the HSL sliders, and then had my color

00:15:49.700 --> 00:15:52.140
palette.

00:15:52.140 --> 00:15:54.900
And finally, I want to talk a little bit about backgrounds.

00:15:54.900 --> 00:16:00.419
So one thing I actually like a lot about the default ggplot theme is that it doesn't

00:16:00.419 --> 00:16:02.539
use a white background.

00:16:02.539 --> 00:16:06.299
White backgrounds are not terrible, there's lots of time and place, but I think they're

00:16:06.299 --> 00:16:10.500
very overused, especially because white is a very harsh color.

00:16:10.500 --> 00:16:14.179
Especially on digital screens, white is a very aggressive and bright color.

00:16:14.179 --> 00:16:19.619
So I encourage you to not necessarily go straight to white as a background as a default, and

00:16:19.619 --> 00:16:21.219
instead explore some other options.

00:16:21.539 --> 00:16:24.539
Recently I've really liked this sort of ivory color.

00:16:24.539 --> 00:16:27.900
A light gray color can also be very nice.

00:16:27.900 --> 00:16:29.940
Or dark backgrounds are fun to experiment with.

00:16:29.940 --> 00:16:34.099
But if you do go with a dark background, just like I don't recommend a pure white background

00:16:34.099 --> 00:16:38.739
all the time, I would be careful unless you have a specific reason about choosing a pure

00:16:38.739 --> 00:16:42.260
black background.

00:16:42.260 --> 00:16:47.500
So to review a little bit, I've talked about how you can establish a good layout in your

00:16:47.500 --> 00:16:52.979
data visualizations by creating clean lines and symmetry, reducing clutter, and increasing

00:16:52.979 --> 00:16:55.059
white space.

00:16:55.059 --> 00:17:01.580
Then you can use good fonts, not use system fonts, and establish a typographic hierarchy

00:17:01.580 --> 00:17:05.099
to help guide readers through your visualization.

00:17:05.099 --> 00:17:09.420
And then hopefully I have given you a little bit of the tools that you need to start coming

00:17:09.420 --> 00:17:14.380
up with your own palettes and choosing your own color palettes.

00:17:14.459 --> 00:17:16.619
So with that, I will say thank you.

00:17:16.619 --> 00:17:18.619
And that's it.

00:17:18.619 --> 00:17:20.619
Thank you.

00:17:20.619 --> 00:17:24.619
Thank you so much, Will.

00:17:24.619 --> 00:17:28.619
I have questions from the audience.

00:17:28.619 --> 00:17:32.619
Tyler, you can come get that up a little if you want.

00:17:32.619 --> 00:17:38.619
The first one is, do you have any specific recommendations for aesthetics for maps?

00:17:38.619 --> 00:17:41.619
Aesthetics for maps.

00:17:41.859 --> 00:17:45.859
I mean, essentially all the same rules apply, right?

00:17:45.859 --> 00:17:51.859
Maps, you want to try to reduce a lot of times the extraneous elements.

00:17:51.859 --> 00:17:55.859
So maps often have a lot of extraneous elements and borders and such.

00:17:55.859 --> 00:17:59.859
And sometimes you're going for a thematic map, you actually might want to emphasize

00:17:59.859 --> 00:18:00.859
those.

00:18:00.859 --> 00:18:05.859
But if you're trying to go for a very clean, easy to read map, you have to think about

00:18:05.859 --> 00:18:06.859
that.

00:18:06.859 --> 00:18:09.859
There's also a lot to be considered in maps with iconography.

00:18:10.099 --> 00:18:14.099
So using proper icons that help readers identify whatever you're looking for.

00:18:14.099 --> 00:18:18.099
Or using a really careful type hierarchy.

00:18:18.099 --> 00:18:22.099
So you have to really, really be careful about your type hierarchy and spend a lot of time

00:18:22.099 --> 00:18:26.099
designing that for a map since you have so many labels and so much type.

00:18:26.099 --> 00:18:27.099
Thanks.

00:18:27.099 --> 00:18:33.099
Next one is, shouldn't a binding constraint for color be colorblind friendliness?

00:18:33.099 --> 00:18:35.099
Yes, absolutely it should.

00:18:35.099 --> 00:18:37.099
I didn't have time to talk about this.

00:18:37.339 --> 00:18:39.339
The slides got cut for time.

00:18:39.339 --> 00:18:42.339
But another very important thing to do in color is accessibility.

00:18:42.339 --> 00:18:46.339
So you should always be checking your color palettes for colorblindness and also for contrast.

00:18:46.339 --> 00:18:50.339
And there's easy websites where you can do that.

00:18:50.339 --> 00:18:55.339
Why is it better for a title to be left aligned instead of centered?

00:18:55.339 --> 00:19:00.339
The reason is mainly because in Western countries, at least, humans read from the top left.

00:19:00.339 --> 00:19:02.339
So that's where your eye goes first on the page.

00:19:02.339 --> 00:19:06.339
There's several eye tracking studies that show that your eye goes first to the top left

00:19:06.579 --> 00:19:08.579
and then to the middle of the page.

00:19:08.579 --> 00:19:12.579
And so putting the title at the top left is basically reducing the amount of work

00:19:12.579 --> 00:19:14.579
that the reader has to do to get to the information.

00:19:14.579 --> 00:19:16.579
Thank you.

00:19:16.579 --> 00:19:18.579
A couple more.

00:19:18.579 --> 00:19:22.579
How long should one typically spend on creating slash designing a chart?

00:19:22.579 --> 00:19:26.579
How long does it typically take you to create one?

00:19:26.579 --> 00:19:28.579
To create a simple design?

00:19:28.579 --> 00:19:30.579
Like something I would do for fidelity?

00:19:30.579 --> 00:19:34.579
You know, something that just needs to look clean and readable?

00:19:34.579 --> 00:19:38.579
I would spend, I don't know, maybe a couple hours designing a chart.

00:19:38.579 --> 00:19:42.579
If I'm designing something more thematic or something for sort of a personal project,

00:19:42.579 --> 00:19:46.579
something more creative, I mean, it can take months.

00:19:46.579 --> 00:19:50.579
You know, it's not all months of sitting down just like designing nonstop for eight hours a day.

00:19:50.579 --> 00:19:54.579
But it's months of like laying in bed at 4 a.m. thinking about colors.

00:19:54.579 --> 00:19:56.579
So...

00:19:56.579 --> 00:19:58.579
That's it.

00:19:58.579 --> 00:20:00.579
Thoughts on Tufti-themed charts?

00:20:00.579 --> 00:20:02.579
I like it.

00:20:02.579 --> 00:20:04.579
That's all I'll say.

00:20:04.579 --> 00:20:06.579
Okay. Great.

00:20:06.579 --> 00:20:08.579
And then...

00:20:08.579 --> 00:20:12.579
Oh, what tool has been used for creating the presentation slides?

00:20:12.579 --> 00:20:14.579
The presentation slides were created with Keynote.

00:20:14.579 --> 00:20:16.579
And let me emphasize, actually, I want to clarify.

00:20:16.579 --> 00:20:18.579
I like the Tufti R Markdown theme.

00:20:18.579 --> 00:20:20.579
I don't always agree with everything Tufti says.

00:20:20.579 --> 00:20:24.579
So Tufti, if you read like his DataVis books, he has a lot of opinions.

00:20:24.579 --> 00:20:26.579
I don't agree with all of those.

00:20:26.579 --> 00:20:30.579
But there's a Tufti R Markdown theme that's based on some of his writings,

00:20:30.579 --> 00:20:32.579
which I really like.

00:20:32.579 --> 00:20:36.579
And then last one before we let Tyler get going is...

00:20:36.579 --> 00:20:42.579
How do you deal with viewers using monitors that might render colors slightly differently?

00:20:42.579 --> 00:20:44.579
Yeah, that's a good question.

00:20:44.579 --> 00:20:46.579
I mean...

00:20:46.579 --> 00:20:48.579
There's very little you can do about that, to be honest.

00:20:48.579 --> 00:20:52.579
I don't have a magical solution to change everyone's monitors for you.

00:20:52.579 --> 00:20:56.579
All I can say is that we are lucky to live in 2020 when people have...

00:20:57.579 --> 00:20:59.579
Most people have more high-resolution monitors,

00:20:59.579 --> 00:21:03.579
so we can use things like fonts that have a lot of details in them

00:21:03.579 --> 00:21:06.579
and, you know, nice color palettes.

00:21:06.579 --> 00:21:08.579
But it's tricky.

00:21:08.579 --> 00:21:11.579
Well, thank you so much. Another round of applause for Willow.

00:21:11.579 --> 00:21:13.579
All right. Thanks.

